        <h1><i class="fas fa-globe"></i> Temporal Horizon</h1>
        <p>
            The Temporal Horizon is a key concept in the Unified Universe Theory, describing the boundary between what we perceive as the present moment and the regions of time that lie beyond our observation. In this framework, the "present" is just a slice of time, a thin layer in the fourth dimension that we experience as the current moment.
        </p>
        <p>
            Beyond this slice lies the Temporal Horizon, an area where events are either yet to happen or have already occurred, making them inaccessible to us. The Temporal Horizon represents the limits of our perception within the time dimension, much like how the event horizon of a black hole represents the boundary beyond which nothing can escape.
        </p>
        <p>
            Anything that crosses the Temporal Horizon moves out of our observable universe, much like how objects can move out of our spatial field of view. This is why certain phenomena, such as dark matter or events far into the future or past, remain beyond our direct observation.
        </p>

        <!-- Simplified Explanation -->
        <h2><i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> Simplified Explanation</h2>
        <p>
